The tenant of Bakal: The stoves are heating, he signed a higher rent.
An imposing elderly man came out of the door of the RPG Byty customer centre of the "coal baron" Zdenek Bakal, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
He carried under his arm a file with three new leases for three apartments: his own, that of his daughter and son who is serving a sentence.
Deregulation has increased the rent for these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 second category apartment 4100 crowns.
"And there is no hot water and the heating works with solid fuel", points out on his son's new contract the man who has the power of signature.
"But I signed it anyway," he explains, moaning angry and half resigned.
The citizens' association of BytyOKD.cz apartments which has described the new rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until December 7, the date on which a notice will be published explaining the method to be followed to claim.
But the man reacts to this by a gesture of the hand.
"One says that, the other says something else" by frowning.
The Ostrava region became the laboratory for deregulation.
After the New Year, this is what awaits most apartments in the Czech Republic whose rents do not match the market price.
Aktualne.cz therefore decided to visit the "laboratory" personally.
The waiting room of RPG in Havirovska Street is one of the four in the Ostrava region and is already full on Tuesday at 9 a.m.
Right next door stands a guard of a security company with a device to call customers.
A special button, "Loyer 2011", is on the touch screen.
Only one pressure and one paper with a number comes out of the device.
You don't have time to read your number "157" that your number already starts to light up on the big screen under the top of the waiting room.
In a fraction of a second it's your turn.
After a short while, an old couple arrives to find out about rent, but the new rents do not seem to concern people in the waiting room.
The majority of people came to solve common problems like everywhere - demand for repairs, insurance events and others.
In the Ostrava region, people from more than 44000 apartments in RPG's portfolio receive mail with new leases in their mailbox since about mid-November.
RPG Byty offers rent increases of 15 to 38 per cent.
The special window for new rents has been open to the public since 18 November.
"It has been working for almost a week, so it's still on trial," answers, after a moment of hesitation, the employee behind the window when the client presents himself as a journalist.
The deragulation and former apartments of minors of Bakal are a very sensitive local subject.
The vice-president of parliament and from the region of Ostrava Lubomir Zaoralek of the Social Democrats reported this in a fairly sustained manner before the elections and it now fills the local newspapers.
"20 years after them, I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change me a put...n board in the toilets, relieves himself in introduction the man mentioned.
However, it is mostly, according to employees, retirees who come to make sure that they will receive a discount on the new rent price if they sign now as promised by RPG in a special offer.
This is a discount of half the amount of rent that will be received by the other lessees who have signed their new contract before December 15.
But the "deregulation" window on Havirovaska Street is really not overwhelmed by the questions.
