Devices to follow people are increasingly required by parents who want to watch over their children.
Fear for their child leads more and more people to think about watching them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can also be used to trace the movement of people and help for some cases as exemple that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a match box but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka moved a large number of people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not spying but only another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, one of the Czech market's suppliers of tracking devices.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware of it, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
"The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons," says Pilin.
According to him children should always know for what purpose "the box" is used and how to use it in an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to deal with him something of this type, he will get rid of it.
'And even the smaller ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something on purpose when they don't want to be under control'.
"Mobile phones, which can cut themselves like these tracking devices, have already led parents to long expectations," says Bockova.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of an attack is highly questionable.
"If it is a prepared abduction, the author will do everything possible to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him."
"Currently, it's the phone."
"As soon as the tracing devices develop, they (the criminals) will also seek them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign".
"In such cases criminals will always be ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
She admits, however, that such devices can help in an assault not prepared by a paedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, it says that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the case of an assault.
"The apparatus may be configured in such a way that it is in regular emission after a specified period of time".
"In the event that the device is destroyed, it remains the last position of the data subject".
"The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and finds himself in a lying position without moving," says Cech.
According to him the so-called smart mobile phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after formatting it with a special prological.
The problem with current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those worn as a pendant the size of a match box or the smallest telephone sets.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being conducted to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"It will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he'll realize it after a while, which will give the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as for tracing cars.
This is a combination of GPS position acquisition systems (which is commonly used in auto-navigation) and a mobile phone function that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
