At the Land Fund in Plzen, the police made arrests during a public competition
In the Land Fund building in Plzen, anti-corruption police have made arrests in recent days.
The detectives passed the handcuffs to the local entrepreneur and shopper in Lubos real estate.
The latter had endeavoured to manipulate a public tender for the settlement of a request for restitution in such a way that the proposed land was obtained by a particular candidate.
This one had to pay Lubos G. half a million crowns.
"For the moment I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for insider trading in the context of a public tender and competition," said for the newspaper Pravo the head of the Prosecutor's Office of Plzen Antonie Zelena, knowing that it is forbidden to provide more explanations because the investigation is under way.
The police released the 46-year-old entrepreneur after 24 hours.
To know how it could affect a public competition, one can only speculate in view of so little official information.
On a question from Pravo, the spokesman of the Lubomira Cerna Land Fund stated that the police had actually made an arrest in Plzen at a separate place of work during the public competition.
"It was a client and under no circumstances an employee," she said.
The public competition according to Cerna has as its real name "Call to propose rights for the transfer of land according to the Land Act" and is set up when several legal candidates manifest themselves.
"These persons propose, in the context of the appeal, a higher value of their rights to re-securities which must be settled before the value of the land is announced".
"According to the proposed rights a ranking of the buyers is set up and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who proposed the highest rights", explained the spokesperson of the Fund.
Lubos G. had, it is clear, the information concerning the persons who had registered for the appeal and since he is himself, also, a beneficiary because he had bought a large number of restitution rights, he had offered the candidates on the ground not to participate in the competition.
And he probably cashed in by withdrawing.
Which would explain why he had so much money in his possession at the time of his arrest.
Lubos G. had contacts well above the standards at the FdT (Land Fund).
He appeared in the case of the former head of the FdT Vaclav Sankot who was prosecuted in criminal proceedings for publishing land for which the decision to set up a building had already been published.
For example, Lubos G. had obtained land for the construction of public communications, specifically in the place where the artery of access to the industrial zone of Borske Pole was to be built.
Later he exchanged it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is by far superior.
The town hall was forced to accept because otherwise it risked putting the construction in jeopardy by blocking the land.
Households will pay a supplement of about 100 crowns per month for housing.
Households will have to pay a supplement from January not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
Families will therefore have to draw from their wallets from January up to a hundred crowns monthly more than now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas by almost 2 percent more expensive, in some localities you will have to pay up to one-tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to be close to 100 more kroner per apartment per year than at present.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices given the significant development in encouraging the manufacture of renewable energy, particularly photovoltaic batteries.
The gas increases moderately but of course at a time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the greatest consumption.
One can therefore also count a hundred more crowns.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in central heating prices differs from city to city.
It is mainly the largest municipalities that plan to increase prices.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay from January for central heating almost 50 more crowns per month, the families of Libérec will pay more than 1,000 crowns annually.
For the inhabitants of Prague is preparing a 9 percent increase in water and sanitation for the case where the city increases the infrastructure rents.
If the rents do not change the pragons will pay an extra 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest compared to the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation increase by 7.4 percent.
Rent prices will increase significantly, for example, in the 450 thousand apartments rented from January onwards, i.e. at the end of the regulation.
For example the company CPI Byty which owns in Usti nad Labem almost 2500 apartments, has decided an increase up to 100 percent.
Those who do not agree with the new increase in rents will be brought before the courts by the company.
The regulated rents that people pay in nearly 300 thousand apartments could increase next year by 10 percent.
