"They are better off because they spend an excellent evening then a sweet awakening and nothing hurts them".
"They are only surprised at where they are," adds Pelikan, knowing that from time to time this spoils the good mood of patients at least with the note to pay for their care.
Ambulance transport and intensive care bed hospitalization can reach tens of thousands of crowns.
"From time to time, I applied this as a means of education by counting on these children how much their drunkenness cost and that they could spend the whole summer in seasonal work to pay back a single evening," Pelikan added.
However, in his view, the health insurance companies in their declining management, which should recover care expenses from parents, do not deal with cases of children who are drunk.
Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in foreign hands in Spain.
Two L-159 of the five aircraft, against which the Ministry of Defence exchanged Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off Tuesday to Seville, Spain, where the manufacturer of Casa-EADS aircraft is based.
This is the first time that aircraft of this type have become the property of someone other than the Czech army.
However, they have been abroad for demonstration exercises or flights.
These are the two-place versions of the L-159T1 that were up to now in service in the Czech Army and were in flight condition.
The three remaining devices are single-seater versions of the L-159.
They are currently stationed at Aéro Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the press department of the Ministry of Defence, the physical departure of the Vodochody aircraft is currently unknown.
"The L-159 single-seat aircraft planned for the exchange were taken from long-stored aircraft without causing additional charges or investments for the Ministry of Defence."
"The L-159 T1 seats were exchanged in the state," said Pravo Pejsek.
He added that the army would not be left without two seats since the ministry signed an agreement with Aéro Vodochody in May 2009 worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two two-seaters.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second aircraft scheduled for delivery at the end of this year.
According to Pejsek EADS, it is committed to introducing aircraft into the equipment of some Alliance countries.
"In the contract it is clearly stated that the one who takes the L-159 aircraft into account is EADS and that they will be used for the training of pilots from NATO member countries."
"It is therefore the case of the one who takes into account how to achieve this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159 for a Casa plane and the purchase of three other planes for 3.5 billion crowns was approved last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defence did not tender and contacted EADS directly.
The Defence Directorate argued that the exchange ensures a future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aéro Vodochody and only uses 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft will probably have judicial implications.
the European Commission has nevertheless lodged a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence before the European Court of Justice because the planes should have been chosen in the framework of a European-wide tender and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa planes, the last one is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
A longer index than the ring finger is a sign of low cancer risk
Men with a longer index than the ring finger are at a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test of prostate cancer risk, especially for men under the age of 60," declared the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, adds Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Great Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the right hand index shorter than the ring finger.
For them, as for the 19 percent of those who had fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the annular, however, the risk fell to 33 per cent, for men before age 60, the decrease in risk reached 87 per cent.
The length ratio of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates, in particular, different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is testosterone that helps develop prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for TKC that he is aware of this study but that it does not seem to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
