Tang Shenbin was surveying a square in the city as an urban sergeant to training by severely inspecting his nervous charges, issuing low-voice orders with a military authority.
He wanted the female members of chengguan - imposing officials of public order in China, feared and despised for their arbitrary repression and their inclination for violence - to convey a certain impression to a group of spectators.
"Stay straight!"
"Be piercing!"
Show them, he said, "What do pretty girls look like!"
Four girls who had barely spent their teens in white gloves, dressed in identical olive-coloured jackets and trousers, were frozen at the attention of you.
Four pairs of black heeled shoes, aligned to the ruler.
Four neat hats perfectly perched on top of hair attached by a blue and white striped knot.
"Personally, I think they look average," said Mr. Tang, disdainfully.
"The models are pretty."
More than one government has tried to refresh the image of China's urban inspectors.
One city demanded that all new recruits have a higher degree.
Guangdong Province traded grey-green uniforms for a so-called more engaging blue.
Wuhan, in Central China, replaced them with the sharp way: in 2009, a report reported that 50 officers had surrounded an uncontrollable snack cart by throwing black glances, firmly for half an hour, until the hawker packed up his stuff and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 inhabitants in Chengdu, chose to do a major image operation.
Since 2003, the district has completed its urban street police force with 13 women, specially chosen for their appearance, shape and young age.
The idea is to give the police a softer, more feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson could have trouble getting a look at this underground urban brigade of China.
And for good reason, critics will say.
Unlike the police, these officers are only allowed to enforce municipal orders by imposing fines or other administrative sanctions.
But the Chinese media portray the news of a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei province beat an observer to death after he used his mobile phone to film them dispersing a protest against a waste dump.
Last year, a training manual for inspectors in Beijing, stolen and posted online, describes how to effectively defeat offenders without emitting blood.
This year in Shanghai, a watermelon hawker was abandoned with a brain injury after a fight with five officers.
A violent video game, available by online download, shows Chinese inspectors trained in assaulting street vendors.
"Chengguan marked the government," deplored last year China Daily, a national publication, after an umpteenth controversy on tactics.
The newspaper called for a "real complete clean-up."
Skeptics say that the approach is far away.
After the district made an announcement in October to find eight new female recruits, an editorial, published in The Beijing Evening News, wondered whether women had any real jobs or whether they were just tourist entertainment.
The answer seems to be a little bit of both.
The district's announcement required female candidates, between 18 and 22 years old, to have a beautiful silhouette and "the five facial features in the right order."
They must have a larger than average size of 1.6 metres or 5 feet, 2 1⁄2 inches.
Retirement at the age of 26 is compulsory.
The officers stated that the work was physically too painful for women over 25 years of age.
"It's their image that's important," said a certain district officer at Rednet.com, a quasi-government website.
"First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine whether they are appropriate; these are height, weight, facial features, etc."
Then come temperament and "inner qualities."
Chengguan women are like flower vases, he said, adding: "In addition to being vases, they will have other responsibilities.
Zheng Lihua, Deputy Director of the City District Management Office, does not agree with this description.
But he noted that the height requirements were the standard standard in many Chinese job offers for both sexes.
This is the case with the requirement for the order of facial features.
That it means beautiful is a subject of debate among the Chinese.
It is true that disabled or disfigured persons must not apply.
"We can't let a lame person or a hunchback come and serve here," says Zheng.
"He wouldn't give a good image."
Liu Yi, who patrolling Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22 years old and has cheeks with a finely curved mouth.
She does not consider the presentation of her appearance to be sexist, she said.
"Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?" she asked in disillusioned air.
Xu Yang, his 21-year-old dimples colleague, says: "Our job is to present the image of the city."
They did not object to their mandate being limited, they said, because they had greater career ambitions than simply chasing sellers into the alleys where they were supposed to limit their activities.
Every morning, the team faces a dozen street vendors who move quickly on foot or by bike, trying to sell as many breads or bowls of tofu as possible before fleeing.
Master Wang, you have to leave.
"We have already told you several times!", said Mrs. Xu while a salesman fled on foot, temporarily abandoning his noodle cart bike.
Agents describe their duties as monotonous rather than hard.
"It's about the same thing every day," said 20-year-old Huang Jing, who studies post-work marketing.
"Great routine."
One reason is that female agents do not have the power of their male counterparts to confiscate the sellers' goods.
They can only threaten to report offenders to their male superiors.
This tends to protect them from sudden public displays of animosity against bureaucracy that are common throughout China.
This year, hundreds of citizens in Kunming, the capital of Yunnan province, rebelled after false rumours were spread that the chengguan agents had killed a salesman.
In one night, more than a dozen chengguan policemen and agents were injured, 14 government vehicles were hit or set on fire.
Xindu has so far escaped such violence.
But calm is hardly guaranteed.
Just two blocks from placid Baoguang Square, where female officers patrolled that morning, more than 50 people gathered around the corner.
The officers confiscated a motorcycle that was being repaired on the sidewalk rather than in a store, as required by regulations.
The owner of the bike was shouting at the scandal.
