Li Xuedong, 40 years old, a coordinator attached to the men's team, stayed behind, her white badge returned to hide her name.
Like female officers, coordinators - men 40 years of age or older - play a purely supportive role.
Unlike them, they are not trained to maintain a waxy image.
"Sometimes we fight verbally."
"Sometimes we fight physically," Li says in a neutral tone.
"Most of the time, it's the audience that starts."
Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
The Department of Justice prosecutors lifted the criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, arising from a case involving an assistant from an old campaign and his efforts to obtain lobbying work for the wife's husband, announced the senator's lawyers on Wednesday.
The decision puts an end to the most serious legal threat faced by Mr.Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election until the scandal around his case made the national headlines last year and harmed his career.
Mr. Ensign's office stated that he was "very happy" by the decision, the result of a one-year investigation.
The honourable senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Counsel for Mr.Ensign stated that the Department of Justice had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer under investigation and that he did not intend to maintain any charges against him in this matter."
The Department of Justice has refrained from commenting on this matter.
The announcement came as a kind of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, according to which there was significant evidence that Mr. Ensign had conspired to violate a federal criminal prohibition on lobbying.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr.Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain lucrative lobbying to win the silence of Mr.Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Ms. Hampton once served as treasurer in an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; according to the documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator with Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited for one year by law from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
The ethics experts argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to be in contradiction with the so-called ban on the rotating door of lobbying.
According to the evidence that was made public, "there appears to be prima facie evidence of a conspiracy to violate and substantial violation of the revolving door law," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients of a government investigation.
Although the judge of the department refused to explain the reasoning that led to the Ensign decision, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department appeared to be wary of political prosecution after a number of high-level setbacks from its Public Integrity Section, including last year's decision to drop the prosecution of former Senator Ted Stevens for lack of prosecution.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms," said Melanie Sloan, Director General of Citizens for Accountability and Ethics in Washington, a defence group that received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them", she added.
Paul Coggins, Mr. Ensign's senior counsel, stated in an interview that on Monday he had received a telephone call from a Department of Justice prosecutor and a follow-up the following day, telling him that the department was not looking for charges against his client.
Mr.Ensign's team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed on Wednesday in a press release, "acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins refused to clarify the legal arguments he had made to the Public Prosecutor's Office.
"I'm not comfortable getting into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we think they've made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that Mr. Ensign's payment of $96,000 by his parents to the Hamptons violated federal electoral law.
The electoral commission stated that it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a significant Nevada company that has long supported the honourable senator, is a company for which Mr.Ensign helped Mr.Hampton find lobbying work.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was "walking" the Ministry of the Interior on an issue in dispute.
Mr. Ensign also participated in a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to schedule a meeting on behalf of the airline after engaging Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as the fourth-ranked Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for several months, Mr.Ensign stated two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr.Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesperson, Jennifer Cooper, said that the honourable senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and end his investigation.
Senator Ensign is pleased to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she says.
