Can civility bring the cleavages closer together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a forerunner of genuine bipartite cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and Congress leaders produced no breakthroughs on the major issues to be addressed during the "Luck Duck" session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides as well as about the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday's public meeting of the committee on the president's deficit was just as civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect transcending the ideological divide; but that, however, still divides the members.
This is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both parties are now in a period of trial and mutual testing to obtain signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
That is why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too profound to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxation, spending, health care or rights, both parties stay miles away.
However, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed in tone," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Centre for Ethical and Public Policy.
"It's inevitable after the election.
The elections spark partisan passions and then fade away.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the "Luck Duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of them, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise can be envisaged on the extension of unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there was more optimism about a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on "the lame duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warned that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session would not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th congress would meet in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
"Once the things that have to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations," he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared scepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
"I consider most of what is going on between today and 2012 as a pre-spectacle or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012, he said.
The reasons are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, pushing the retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, in their view, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected representatives; this suggests that there is little reason or willingness to compromise on tax issues, at least today.
Galston plans two phases in the fight between the White House and the Republicans of Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan confrontations, as Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care; and then be followed by a period of greater bipartite cooperation.
What would be the cause of change?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
If confrontation leads to an impasse, as in 1995, then both parties will observe the reaction of the public carefully.
He who is judged to be in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would nevertheless be an optimistic point of view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans of Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a larger election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exhibited this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But much more effort will be required on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
American documents leaked describe Moscow as a haven of corruption
Control of the city is in the hands of a "Kleptocracy" and passes through the Kremlin some of the bribes and protection money it collects, the US Embassy in Russia reported in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service carry out huge racketes that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy - what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin called the "vertical of power" - is taking its share as money moves up the ladder.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted Wednesday by Wikileaks on its website.
The note is based on sources whose names have been redacted.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow; and he is largely held responsible for corruption.
He was fired in October by President Dmitri Medvedev, but there has been little clean-up since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Elena Batourina, who owns a leading construction company, have always denied the accusations of corruption over the years; and he has won several defamation lawsuits on these charges.
In September, he told a Russian television channel when he was questioned about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: "It's crazy, it's to throw away, it's anything."
The Russians believe, by an overwhelming majority, that their society is corrupt; according to polls.
But it is unusual to find the information contained in an embassy report; and it is unheard of that it would be up to diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link between the Moscow City government and crime has led some people to name it "dysfunctional" and to assert that the government functioned more like a kleptocracy than a government," according to the embassy's note.
"Criminal elements enjoy a "krysha" (term used in the criminal world/mafia which literally means "roof" or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior (MVD) and the prosecutor's office, as well as through all the bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
"Analysts to identify a three-tier structure in Moscow's criminal world."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The FSB, the MVD and the militias are at the second level."
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"This is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fill a void in certain areas where the city does not provide certain services."
The report indicates that the FSB is brewing money from the largest companies and that the police are targeting the smaller ones.
One source, he said, "explained that business owners in Moscow understood that it was better to get protection from MVD and FSB (rather than organized crime groups) because, not only do they have more weapons, more means and more power than criminal groups but they are also protected by law."
"That's why the demand for protection by criminal gangs is no longer so high."
The note notes that although the collection of money is extensive, protection itself may be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly see their business closed under one pretext or another.
Medvedev has mentioned the fight against corruption several times, but he has admitted that little progress has been made.
The note from the embassy transmits reports of men bringing suitcases, probably full of money, to the Kremlin.
"In its fight against corruption, Medvedev depends on bureaucrats," said in a recent interview with Gueorgui Satarov, director of the "think tank Indem" in Moscow.
"But he's part of this bureaucracy."
"He is not part of a political class because there is no political class in Russia."
Without politics, without opposition, without separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
According to Indiam, the cost of corruption is estimated to be more than $300 billion a year across Russia.
The country was ranked 154th in a recent survey on the overall perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are classified at least as corrupt).
The disclosure of the note of the American embassy, which was only carried out yesterday, late in the evening, Moscow time, will stir with certainty discontents within the Russian government; although Lujkov can be blamed, to some extent, for the failures of Moscow, this could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to show that he is solving the problem.
Interviewed by the CNN by Larry King, Putin hypothesized that WikiLeaks' documents could be a fabrication and reacted with anger to the statements that US diplomats had leaked by calling him Batman and bringing Medvedev closer to Robin.
"The problem lies in the fact that this is our interaction, an important factor in domestic policy in this country," he says.
"But to be honest with you, we did not suspect that it would be achieved with such arrogance, such pressure and, as you know, in opposition to ethics."
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a poorly lit classroom with poor quality decrepit concrete walls, the headmaster of Anlong Veng High School mentioned the man who built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader; and he cared about his people," said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was head of the Khmer Rouge, this commander remains popular in this isolated bastion of former Khmer Rouge in north-west Cambodia where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-standing loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum enabled victims to face publicly the people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of its former soldiers.
And, in July, a Cambodian court, jointly run with the United Nations, handed down its first sentence concerning a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing, to 35 years in prison, the former head of Tuol Sleng's notorious torture centre, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as "Duch".
In the face of these developments, anxiety has increased among the Khmer Rouge veterans of Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their willingness to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There are resentments and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Centre, an independent body that conducts research on the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime became a symbol of evil."
"The situation generates divisions within families."
During the reign of the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrowed Pol Pot's government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurgency that lasted until the last of the movements came in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrillas from their base in the mountains of western Cambodia and the jungle, Ta Mok prepared a sequel to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a United Nations-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, major groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defectionize the government, culminating in the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had stood up, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 pending his trial.
Without their benefactors, most Khmer Rouge veterans have sunk into black poverty, common to the rural areas of Cambodia; and many remain nostalgic to the movement.
Although some Khmer Rouge elite officers retained their positions as local leaders in exchange for laying down their arms, they are low-grade, unskilled farmers.
"These people received very little follow-up after the capitulation," said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They are imbued with the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
"They were raised in a framework where doing business is a foreign concept."
Sor Lim, 55 years old, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice farmer.
"Life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"Your Mok feeds everyone."
But now life is difficult because we have to provide for ourselves."
The ongoing Khmer Rouge Court has also caused concern here.
The court is expected to start the trial at the beginning of next year with Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer red minister.
The court's mandate is to try senior leaders and key perpetrators of crimes, but it did not say whether it was continuing beyond these four cases.
It would take more to calm fears in Anlong Veng.
The latest media speculation turned to Im Chaem, 64 years old, a former district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she had supervised the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project where thousands of forced workers were reportedly killed.
Recently, during a torrid evening, Im Chaem returned from work to the field near his wooden house on stilts, on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows on the dried grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past within the Khmer Rouge.
If the court called her, she said, she would refuse to go.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," she said.
"If there is more prosecution, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defectioned the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the court prosecuted several suspects; although experts and historians dispute this.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But facing the past is all Cambodia has to do to move forward, says Youk Chhang, of the documentation centre.
"The reconciliation in Khmer terms is to reconnect broken pieces," he said.
"We have to put these pieces together so we can understand."
The centre produced the first manual approved by the government on the Khmer Rouge, "A History of Democratic Kampuchea, composed of 75 pages."
He distributed it to Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the history textbooks of the Ministry of Education, designed for higher schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know only a few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, a 19-year-old student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he came home with the book to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court," he says.
"They're suspicious because they don't know exactly how many people the court will go after."
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, said Sok Leang.
But the public forums, the manual and the court are beginning to have an impact, he said.
Yet the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful atrait here.
In the heights of the Dangrek mountains, a path, invaded by weeds and dotted with plastic bags, leads to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a rusted sheet roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31-year-old mobile phone salesman on the roadside, said she didn't know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a great spirit; and many inhabitants go there to pray," she said.
