The second operation was completed on Monday and was carried out by air, according to officials.
The US government has spent $13 million in its efforts, largely to replace Belarus's research facilities with low-enriched uranium; unsuitable for weapons.
"Comprehensive coordination and organization have been implemented to build confidence", leading to the agreement signed by Clinton, said Andrew Bieniawski, head of the Energy Department specializing in Global Threat Reduction.
According to estimates by the James Martin Non-Proliferation Study Centre, Belarus had at least 88 pounds of military-grade uranium this year, as well as hundreds of kilos of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus is seeking to eliminate its stocks by 2012, according to a joint declaration.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly because of Lukashenko's harsh repression of human rights.
