Sport and fraud of the law
The tricks similar to that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the will to escape punishment.
The expulsion of two players from Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the match of November 23rd against Ajax in the Champions League made a lot of ink on the anti-sports character of such behavior and whether the two players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before finishing the game (which their team had already clearly won), both players deliberately lost time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and since Real Madrid will eventually be leader of its group, both players will complete the regulatory sanction during the next game of the barrage game against Auxerre and will be able to pass without boxes to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA Discipline Committee sanctioned with two games the team coach, José Mourinho and various economic sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances such as this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that appeared in the related case was due to the fact that this had been the protagonist of a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and which on past occasions sentenced its players to a fine for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his dilated history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour, not expressly prohibited by the regulation, contradicts the principles of sport, that is to say, whether with these actions one commits a fraud by law; because, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sports regulations, but seem to elude its meaning.
The question is to look at the type of harm they cause to sportsmanship.
One of the assets that understands sportsmanship is the physical integrity of opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been put in danger, i.e. there has been no violent game.
Another of these assets to which reference is made with the correct game is to prevent the team of infractors from profiting in an unfair way from the contrary team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not accommodate itself to what is normally characterized as cheating o fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalization of the referee.
They were waiting and willingly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of advantage that offenders obtain from the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put the rival in a position of disadvantage and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action presupposes leaving their own team with fewer players.
And that's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn't count on these players.
Of course the advantage is that the players will start the next phase of the Champions League without boxes that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty game and pass to the second cycle of cartons, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cartons occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, climbing the ladders, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In the end, these actions are not contrary to the spirit of sport, which is still part of the strategic decision-making that favours the maximum benefit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not operate to avoid the application of the penalty (it would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law),m otherwise they chose rather the time in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without foiling the penalty or running away from it.
Even though the boundary between genius and the fraud of the law is diffuse, on this occasion I think we had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, appears because of two factors: because there were two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the director was transmitted to provoke them.
The evil caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
