The peculiarity of the Pakistani nuclear programme — the fact that weapons are not assembled, but they are stored in components to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack — is one of the main reasons for concern in Washington.
For example, Ambassador Anne W. Patterson of Pakistan listed in a report before the visit of former National Security Adviser James Jones: "The proximity of certain nuclear installations in the territory under Taliban attack, the dispersion of nuclear materials whose noise runs and the vulnerability of the transport of atomic materials".
