Thus, the 188 Interpol countries have been advised to identify or locate Assange "in order to obtain his provisional arrest and extradition".
Although Interpol cannot issue an arrest order for an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, according to the organization's explanation, consider the appeal red notice a free way to arrest -- which the national police force must carry out -- especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case with Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be present.
