Nevertheless, he made it clear that China would not change its objectives, but it would continue to work together with the international community in that area.
He mentioned that China's climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institution building; and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been made in all of these areas, including the approval last year of a new Energy Act, which recognizes the objectives addressed with respect to greenhouse gas reduction, he explained.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China, federal authorities have worked in a coordinated manner with governments and local governments to achieve energy savings, efficient energy use and emission reductions.
In addition, he said, there are various multi-year plans underway or completed, both funded by the Chinese government and by governments of other countries.
For example, he mentioned the Energy Efficiency Program, which has been implemented over the past five years and has received investments from the United Nations (UN), government and private initiative.
