Dupont partially blammed
Quebec radio host Stéphane Dupont suffered a partial setback before the Canadian Broadcast Standards Council (CBSC) for controversial remarks about social assistance and Haitians as well as his coarse language on the air.
The CBSC found that Mr.Dupont and his team of CHOI 98.1 FM had the right to express their opinions, but that some of the comments contained "incorrect information about social assistance, unduly negative representations of Haitians and coarse language that was not suitable for broadcasts during the day."
The Commission also found that a discussion on suicide, including the broadcast of the names of two individuals who committed suicide, did not violate the broadcasting codes.
The CBSC had received several complaints about comments made during broadcasts between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was made following a complaint by the Front commun des personnes aides sociales du Québec.
The group complained that the amounts quoted in the issue were inaccurate.
Facilitators must present sound rather than misleading information.
Regarding suicide, host Stéphane Dupont had considered suicide to be a coward's gesture.
The majority of Committee members concluded that the message was that suicide should not be seen as a solution to life's problems.
"The majority of the Committee considers that the episodes in question of "Dupont le midi" addressed a sensitive issue in a fair and appropriate manner."
No reprimand was therefore held against him.
The last dispute concerned statements that followed the earthquake in Haiti.
Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort had then engaged in a media face-to-face that had elicited a lot of reactions.
The host of CHOI said that he had made no donation to help Haitians because we could not know with certainty that the needy people would really receive the money.
The Committee believes that these comments were not abusive, but that their cumulative effect constitutes an unduly negative representation of Haitians.
"I've already purged my three-day suspension on this."
"My file has been blank for a year and a half," the host said.
In all decisions, the Committee denounces the dissemination of coarse language.
In each case, the broadcaster CHOI-FM collaborated "beyond its obligation".
The consequences are minimal for the station, which must, among other things, announce these decisions once during prime time within three days.
King of Kung Fu in Montreal
The Montrealer of Algerian origin Nacereddine Zemmal has an extremely special course.
The athlete who excels in "sanda" (kung-fu "full contact"), kickboxing and Thai boxing climbs on the tatamis and rings of the world in search of new challenges.
"I started practicing martial arts such as kung fu and kickboxing 12 years ago in Algeria," said Zemmal, who has been based in the metropolis since 2008 to evolve among professionals."
"In my case, I'm looking for fights everywhere, because for those who don't like ground play in mixed martial arts, competitions are rare in North America."
Recently, one who works as a security officer and clerk for UPS has just released bad news to his rivals, winning two gold medals at the World Karate and Kickboxing Association (WKA) Amateur World Championship, October 23-30, Edinburgh, Scotland.
"I won the kickboxing full contact and Thai boxing categories," he explained.
"Currently, I'm getting ready to go to China for the San Shou World Cup."
"The fighters who finished among the top four in the last world championship in each category were invited."
"I won bronze in 2009 in Toronto."
"In 2005, in Vietnam, I finished eighth."
"In 2007, in China, I concluded the tournament in fifth place, while I was third in Toronto in 2009, he added."
"What's interesting is that I've made progress in every competition."
"At this rate, I will be first this time or next year!"
The "san shou" or "sanda" is a discipline originating in China where punches and kicks, as well as projections on the ground, are allowed.
Duels take place originally on a platform and more rarely in a ring.
The most famous Puglist from this form of combat is the Vietnamese-born American Cung Le, well-known in the world of martial arts.
If Nacer Zemmal has only one event in his career, he will certainly answer his presence at the super tournament "King of Sanda", the Kung-fu Super Bowl.
"This competition is the highest and most prestigious in China," explained the friendly fellow."
"It's kind of the equivalent of the Lumpinee Stadium (the biggest stadium in Thailand)."
"It was a great experience."
Zemmal won his first fight, in the semi-final of his category (80 kg), before losing in the final.
"He who defeated me was a real pro," he analyzed.
"There are four fighters per category (80 kg, 85 kg, 90 kg and 90 kg)."
"The winners of the semi-finals compete in the finals of their category."
"Then the winners of each category face each other in order to crown only one champion, the king of kung fu."
450 million in contracts without invitations to tender
Hydro-Québec has awarded $450 million in contracts to engineering firms for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of more than 100 contracts, it was a consortium of BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor firms that obtained the largest amount, the project's management, for $295 million without any tender.
This consortium called Energy Stewardship was formed in 2004 in conjunction with Hydro-Québec's choice to entrust the private sector with its responsibility to manage this major $5 billion hydroelectric project.
At the beginning of 2005, the Energy Stewardship Consortium issued the lucrative contract without a public tender.
For the Parti Québécois, the use of consortia of companies poses a serious ethical problem that risks eliminating competition and causing price increases.
"It's the new way of collusion and cutting down on competition."
"In other words, people, instead of secretly doing this, now do it in an open way," said MP Sylvain Simard at a press conference yesterday.
Earlier in the morning, Mr. Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because he says he has difficulty seeing how the public interest can be served in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, replied in the afternoon, vigorously denying that there had been collusion for this contract.
"I'm starting to have my trip," she pestered, arguing that the PQ had been "unethical" and had "lacked rigour."
She said that "it would be the least thing" that the PQ apologized.
The consortium formula is a common practice worldwide.
This is usually a time-limited alliance that allows two or more companies to pool their respective expertise in order to respond to a call for tenders for a complex project.
The Eastmain project has a high level of complexity given the scale of the work.
The project is in progress and is scheduled to run until 2012.
However, the contract was awarded without competition; negotiations took place.
Also, the consortium formula is no longer an exception in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As revealed last week by Le Devoir, the consortium formula in the consulting engineering sector is under investigation in the government.
A quick overview of Quebec's business register allows more than 200 consortia to be counted, some of which seem permanent.
Thus, Dessau works in partnership with most of its main competitors, including CIMA+, Genivar, SNC-Lavalin and others Roche and Tecsult.
Each combination, and there are dozens, brings back to one and the same legal person, Dessau.
With respect to the Energy Stewardship Consortium, Minister Normandeau noted that "the territory of James Bay responds to particular labour force dynamics and that Hydro-Québec has responded to them in a particular way since the 1970s."
The major manager of the Eastmain Project, Réal Laporte, of the James Bay Energy Corporation (JSB), gave an explanation that caused the project's management contract to swirl over.
"If you go to tender and there are few bidders, your prices will be higher."
"You have two choices: either you take the people who are in that market and say: we're going to negotiate a satisfactory deal with a good price."
"But the idea is that it is not the price that is important, it is the competence of people," Laporte said.
This contract awarded to the Energy Stewardship Consortium is part of a long list of contracts over $50,000 obtained by the Parti Québécois.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Québec or SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
After verification, Le Devoir counted 109 consulting engineering contracts awarded between 2002 and March 2010 to firms or their subsidiaries, including soil laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin won 22 contracts, Genivar won 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, not to mention his participation in Energy Stewardship.
All contracts have been negotiated.
They total $449,783,344, including the $295,131,564 Energy Stewardship contract.
Sylvain Simard suggested that the four companies that make up the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) are "well known to the Quebec Liberal Party".
Minister Normandeau let go that the PQ is also linked to these firms that "finance it", before making it clear that it was rather its leaders.
Responsible Consumption Barometer - The "green" label does not inspire confidence
Greener, but frankly sceptical.
Quebec consumers have very little confidence in the players involved in sustainable development, but also in fair brands and greening certifications to guide their choices.
Worse, even if he bathes in a media world where messages in favour of more responsible consumption are growing, he deplores a lack of credible information, which he even describes as a brake on his commitment, says the Barometer of Responsible Consumption, whose first reading was delivered yesterday.
Although they increased the consumption of so-called socially responsible products in 2010, Quebecers seem to give very little credit to those who try to sell them.
Two thirds of them say they do not believe the environmental commitment of companies as well as the companies' green advertising, reveals the measurement tool developed by the Observatoire de la consommation responsable at Université Sherbrooke.
Another observation: half of consumers doubt the reliability of official certifications on so-called fair products, but also the credibility of products and brands showing themselves to be eco-responsible, says the Barometer.
In the same vein, politicians' speeches on this topic are taken seriously by only 14.6% of Quebecers.
However, information on responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this segment of consumption currently driven by almost a third of Quebec consumers.
Indeed, the vacuum and dubious nature of the information would calm the ardours of 46% of consumers.
This is the second brake identified by the Barometer, after the higher price of these products.
In addition, one third of Quebecers say they are equally suspicious of the alleged performance of green products or services that are being put in their hands.
On another note, consumers were almost half in 2010 to have changed their habit and, above all, to have changed the brand of one or more products to meet their conviction.
At 61%, they have also favoured purchases from local traders and the purchase of food products grown in their area, says the Barometer.
Greener and more responsible - the responsible consumption index has reached 64 out of a maximum of 100 for this year - the Homo consumer of Quebec likes to present itself as the king of recycling who seeks to reduce its environmental footprint by worrying about the protection of animals.
But his social and ecological awareness seems to remain outside his car, says the Barometer: in 2010, just 28% of Quebecers said they used public transit or advocated carpooling to defend their green interests.
Walking and cycling were also supported by 39.1% of participants in this vast behavioural survey, which has just taken its first shot.
A government loan for the purchase of eXcentris
The Government of Quebec, which was asked to make a financial commitment to the acquisition of the cinema complex eXcentris by Société Angus and Le Parallèle, agrees to cooperate, but up to one loan only.
The Société de développement Angus and the Parallèle, hoping for a donation of $7 million from the Ministry of Culture to buy from Daniel Langlois the cinema complex eXcentris on Saint-Laurent Boulevard by giving him his full cinephilic vocation, did not get what they demanded.
The government agrees to be involved in the matter, but on its own terms.
Rather than the expected gift, the Government of Quebec is proposing a loan that would be less than the original expectations, which could be a viable solution on advantageous terms, at least in the opinion of the sources from the Crown's compendia.
A first action plan and a request of 12.8 million had already been rejected by Quebec last spring, but the requests have since been revised downwards.
A proposal and an action plan were sent to Minister St-Pierre by the President of the Société de développement des entreprises culturelles (SODEC), François Macerola, who is piloting the eXcentris case.
He sent him a final report about ten days ago.
But the firm's counter-proposal came to SODEC on Tuesday.
The Parallel and Angus have until 31 December to respond.
It seems, however, that the hypothesis of the gift of the State really has to be ruled out.
Recall that the Association des propriétaires de cinémas et de cinéparcs du Québec opposed a direct investment by the state to support the acquisition of eXcentris, arguing that the Ministry of Culture does not have to finance real estate projects, which it has not done for other cinemas.
On the contrary, a number of stakeholders in the community called for substantial economic assistance.
Daniel Langlois, the master of ceans, for ten years carried the author's cinema to his premises of the complex after having financed his own construction, which could justify a derogation on the part of the Conseil du trésor.
The lack of theatres for independent films is crying out in Montreal, and eXcentris had been able to retain its clientele.
The Société Angus and the Parallel, headed by Christian Yaccarini, are piloting a private fundraising campaign, hoping to raise $700,000 to push the acquisition wheel.
Since spring 2009, only one of the three screens, Le Parallèle, has continued to broadcast films in eXcentris.
The aim of the future buyers is to reopen the three theatres on February 27 by screening the beautiful film by Xavier Beauvois Des hommes et des Dieus.
But Christian Yaccarini did not recall Le Devoir and we do not know what he and his group think of the downward proposals made to them.
The veil raised over a complex Canada...
The new U.S. diplomatic cables released by WikiLeaks shed light on what the U.S. considers to be the inferiority complex of Canadians to the Americans, but at the same time they betray their sense of superiority over Canada.
Thus, U.S. diplomats are surprised that every Canadian voter does not have Canada-U.S. relations in mind by going to vote and believe that President Obama's visit helped the Conservative government pass its budget in 2009!
The four new communications between the U.S. Embassy in Ottawa and Washington, spread out in the public square yesterday, offer more crispy details than substantial content to put under the tooth.
A cable dated September 22, 2008, in the midst of a federal election campaign, tells how much the United States is not one of the issues discussed by political leaders.
To the great astonishment of the U.S. ambassador in Ottawa, David Wilkins.
Mr Wilkins offered some explanation for this situation.
"An almost inherent Canadian inferiority complex may make it necessary for Canadian political leaders to talk about domestic issues in everyday life rather than to have this election focused on the United States (as in the 1988 Free Trade Campaign)," he writes.
The United States is therefore, he concludes, "the proverbial elephant of this election: omnipresent, but potentially too threatening to talk about it".
The ambassador understands all the less this deafening "silence" because the two countries have an intense political and economic relationship.
"Logically, he believes, the ability of a candidate, a party and even more a party leader to manage this essential relationship should be a key factor that voters have in mind when going to vote."
The other expression of this sense of importance is in the cable sent on January 22, 2009 by Terry Breese, Chargé d'affaires in Ottawa, preparing President Barack Obama for his first visit to Ottawa.
"Your trip will help ensure the government's survival in the confidence vote on the federal budget in early February, by which Canada will have its first deficit in more than a decade because of a recovery plan of $30 to $40 billion," Breese writes.
Nowhere is it mentioned that the government had to extend Parliament before Christmas to avoid being overthrown by the coalition and that the opposition parties made its survival conditional on the quality of the proposed stimulus plan.
Another communication, dated January 2008 and signed by Ambassador Wilkins, warns Washington of the increasingly negative image that CBC drama shows are sending back from the United States.
The Ambassador is concerned about Border, Little Mosque on the Prairie, Intelligence and H2O programs, in which there are unsubtle references to Maher Arar, the No-Fly-List, or abductions for CIA muscle interrogations.
Another cable relates that, at their first bilateral meeting, Hillary Clinton asked his French counterpart Bernard Kouchner if Europe was ready to welcome some prisoners from Guantánamo.
Mr Kouchner answered yes, but on the basis of "case by case".
At the end of the meeting, it is written, "he handed over a paper to the Secretary of State about Omar Khadr, a 15-year-old Muslim of Canadian origin."
"The secretary has agreed to review the file."
Let's finally note that the spirits are warming up about the WikiLeaks website.
Tom Flanagan, a former advisor very close to Stephen Harper, said on CBC that the person responsible for this massive leak should be "murdered".
He echoed Mike Huckabee in the United States.
A global plan to renovate lighting
Yesterday in Cancún, the United Nations proposed a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gases (GHGs), which corresponds to almost one third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in line with the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to have adopted in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market were replaced by compact fluorescent bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diode bulbs (LED or "LED" in English), the bulk of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHGs emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
That's the equivalent of 70% of global car fleet emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase aggregate GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to subtract from this balance sheet still 5 Gt in order to stabilize by 2020 the rise of the climate to 2 degrees centigrades in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In incandescent ampoules, 95% of the energy dissipates as heat and the rest, 5%, produces light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this need for energy is reduced by twice again.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, like those launched by manufacturer Philips this week - this company participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent light bulb, giving an idea of the possible economy with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These all new bulbs can also work with rheostates in addition to emitting very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
A number of specialists have posted reserves for compact fluorescent light bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place guidelines.
But, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact bulb, but rather the coal-fired thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make as a result of this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants, the construction of which would cost it 2.5 billion.
Côte d'Ivoire waits for the announcement of election results in the nervousness
The UN Secretary-General, Ban Ki-moon, called for the publication "without delay" of the results of the presidential election in Côte d'Ivoire, after the deadline has expired.
"The Secretary-General stresses the need for the Independent Electoral Commission to complete its work and announce the provisional results without further delay," said a spokesman for the UN leader.
"It calls on all Ivorian parties and institutions to show responsibility and refrain from any initiative until the provisional results are announced."
Despite pressure from some foreign governments, the election commission missed the deadline of Wednesday midnight without publishing the results, three days after Sunday's election.
About forty minutes before the deadline expired, the president of the CIS had told television that the commission was "continuing to work" to announce the results.
The calls multiplied on Wednesday in the world for the CIS to finally announce the name of the winner of the second round between the outgoing Laurent Gbagbo and the opponent Alassane Ouattara.
But the Gbagbo camp is counting on the Constitutional Council to cancel "faudulous" votes in the north, held by the ex-rebellion of the Forces nouvelles (FN) since the failed coup d'état of September 2002.
Pascal Affi N'Guessan, campaign director of the Ivorian president, said that the intimidation of voters by the FN in the north of the country had deterred supporters of the outgoing president from going to vote.
The whole election could be cancelled if Gbagbo's complaints were upheld by the Constitutional Council.
Gbagbo's opponents believe that the highest court in the country is not neutral because it is led by Paul Yao N'Dré, a close political ally of Gbagbo.
Alassane Ouattara, a northern man who denies any connection with the former rebels, considered "unacceptable" the delay in announcing the results and asked Gbagbo to respect them, but he did not go so far as to claim victory.
His allies claim that Gbagbo is blocking the publication of the results because he knows that he has lost and that bringing a complaint to the Constitutional Council, after preventing the electoral commission from disseminating the results, would be illegal.
The second round of the presidential election, on Sunday, was supposed to crown the process of reunification and reconciliation of a country that had been split in two for years.
On Wednesday, the United Nations warned the Ivorian political class that it could be held responsible for possible violence.
Laurent Gbagbo had finished in the lead of the first round, on 31 October, with 38% of the votes against 32% in Alassane Ouattara, which received the public support of former president Henri Konan Bédié (25% in the first round).
The unemployment rate remained stable in France in the third quarter
The unemployment rate in France within the meaning of the International Labour Office (ILO) remained stable at 9.3% in metropolitan France (9.7% including the overseas departments), show the provisional seasonally adjusted data (CVS) published on Thursday by INSEE.
The number of unemployed is 2,631 million in metropolitan France.
Data for the second quarter were confirmed to 9.3% of the working population in metropolitan France and 9.7% with the DOMs.
Over a year, the unemployment rate is rising by 0.1 percentage points.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not they were available within two weeks to work and whether or not they were looking for a job.
The situation of young people on the labour market has deteriorated further, with a further rise in the unemployment rate, rising to 24.2% in metropolitan France (+ 0.9 points over three months + 0.5 points over one year) and 25% including the French overseas departments.
In the third quarter, 637,000 young people between the ages of 15 and 24 were unemployed within the meaning of the ILO.
Seniors, for their part, experienced a slight increase in unemployment, to 6.4% in metropolitan France (+0.2 points over three months and also over one year), i.e. 482,000 people aged 50 or over, and 6.6% with the DOMs.
Only 25-49 year-olds benefited from stable unemployment in the third quarter, 8.3% in metropolitan France (-0.1 point over three months, +0.1 point over one year) and 8.8% throughout France.
INSEE has not published monthly unemployment rates since 2006, after a controversy about its method of calculation.
Eurostat, the statistical agency of the European Union, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (including DOM) in October after 9.9% in September.
Alexandre Guérini charged and placed in detention
