Finally, Alexandre Guérini's companion, Jeannie Peretti, was charged for "recel of abuse of social goods".
Among the people who have been confronted with Mr Guérini is Stéphane Brunengo-Girard, who was recently imprisoned in a parallel case of fraudulent public procurement affecting Corsica.
Investigators suspect his companies were used to launder money from big banditry.
The investigation is carried out within the framework of several judicial information opened against X in April 2009 following anonymous mails, for alleged frauds in the award of public contracts, in particular in the waste sector.
From a source close to the survey, the investigations focus in particular on the conditions for the allocation and operation of a landfill in La Ciotat, which collects waste from Aubagne as well as from certain cities in the urban community of Marseille (MPM).
Clotilde Reiss case: the Elysée exaggerated Syria's mediation
For more than ten months, from July 2009 to May 2010, the fate of Clotilde Reiss, the young French researcher arrested in Iran for "espionage", held the public in breath in France, put diplomacy on alert, and accentuated the deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
All under the watchful gaze of the diplomats of the United States.
The American documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by Le Monde reveal some of the undersides of this crisis.
They describe how the Elysée explained its strategy to the Americans, even giving them advice on how to deal with their own "hostage" crises in Iran (a small group of hikers).
They show how the French officials tried to convince Washington that the release of the young French woman had not been matched by the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian detained in France and wanted by the American courts for trafficking in materials for the benefit of Iran's nuclear programme.
Finally, they place under a harsh light the way the French presidency sought to manipulate the media to accredit the idea that Syrian President Bashar Al-Assad had played a central role in the liberation of Clotilde Reiss.
In reality, this was not the case.
A diplomatic telegram written on 12 August 2009 in Paris is entitled "Iran: French comments on how to deal with hostage cases".
The Elysée Advisor for Strategic Affairs, François Richier, accompanied by the Director of the Quai d'Orsay for North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, meet with the American diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
They explain the French method to him.
They advise the Americans to do the same to repatriate their own forcibly held nationals to Iran.
"Make noise," they say, "get the words "fundamental human rights," "innocent," "immediate release" in the media.
It is necessary in order to embarrass the Iranian regime, sensitive to its image.
"Do it all the more because the Iranians are asking you not to do it."
For, past attempts to discuss through discreet channels, "silence will not settle anything", the Iranians are "masters in dilatory maneuvers".
Mr Richier adds that the arrest of foreigners is "a familiar Iranian tactic: taking hostages for political blackmail".
He announces that the release of Clotilde Reiss from prison (which will take place on 16 August, the day she takes refuge at the French Embassy) "will require the payment of a large amount of money to Iranians" (€230,000 in bail).
And he says that the Elysée anticipates other hostage crises, a phenomenon that "will worsen".
Iranians could "in the near future arrest another of some 1,800 French citizens living in Iran," he says.
28 August 2009.
Clotilde Reiss has been out of prison for 12 days, but remains stuck in Iran.
Information is being disseminated: Iran's Majid Kakavand, whose extradition the United States is demanding for illegal trafficking of sensitive electronic equipment to Iran, is released in Paris, by a judge's decision.
The American Embassy, like many observers, wonders about this disturbing coincidence.
For Washington, which is tracking Iran's clandestine procurement networks for nuclear programme equipment, the expansion of Majid Khakavand is bad news.
Did France accept a bargain?
The liberation of the Iranian from that of the French?
In a further interview with Kathleen Allegrone on 4 September, François Richier assures that this is not the case.
The Elysée, he said, was not only "completely taken by surprise by the judge's decision", but sought to oppose it.
"There was a lively exchange between the French presidency and the keeper of the seals" (at the time, Michèle Alliot-Marie), but "the French government cannot go back on the decision" judicially, he observes.
