Hackers vengeful and spies in diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it turns out to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and prefigures a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that each file made up of a secret service (of any nation) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those of which Berlusconi is the owner), and Khadafi's sinister caricature profile has long been for cabaret artists to sketch.
The rule that secret files should be composed only of new ones already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in previous books.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do new research (no know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe only in what they already know, and reconfirm what they had already learned.
It's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
Same for secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) the head of the secret services (if not he could be, what do I know, editor of Libération), who holds as true only what he recognizes.
The top secret information on Berlusconi sent by the American Embassy in Rome to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
Then why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every cultured person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of state can phone themselves or take a plane to meet at dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small performance exercises, have turned into spy centres.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that we pretend to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to place American diplomacy in the wrong light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
So the scandal does not put the victims in so much crisis as the "bourreaux".
But let us come to the deep nature of what has happened.
Once, in Orwell's time, we could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely established since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway used and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when we show, as happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
The power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as a citizen's avenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is true, too, that all knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret of secret, because it falls within the public domain; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to remove all power.
WikiLeaks did no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but made it too big to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury to a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, the states will no longer be able to post any reserved information - that would be to publish it on a poster stuck at the corner of the street.
But it is equally obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to expect to be able to maintain confidential reports over the telephone.
Nothing easier than to find out if and when a head of state moved by plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my forecast is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in uncontrollable stages, carrying only messages learned by heart or, at most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept as a single copy in locked drawers: in the background, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in crab, i.e. backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wire telegraph (telephones).
The videocassettes (analogical) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and backwards and discovering all the secrets of editing, while now the CDs (digital) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we travel from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that communications policy and techniques should go back to horse-drawn cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was going on in the secret of embassies.
Now it is the embassies that ask the press for confidential information.
Climate: how France interferes with its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine the fulfilment of the fast-start or early-start financing commitments made by developed countries.
And the big French tweaks are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries committed $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (or 420 million a year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU released the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the action of its member states, press conference, big side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency exercise is appreciated and appreciated: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
In 2010, the EU announced that it had committed €2.2 billion, putting it on the right track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, this money must be "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being to the detriment of Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
In contrast, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to previous years' expenditures or to the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
In concrete terms, France's total amount of support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to fulfil its commitment to "new and additional" funding...
Another crucial element is the distribution between grants and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1€ loaned is equivalent to 1€ given.
Obviously, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
While the use of loans can be justified for some profitable investments (often projects related to mitigation of emissions that rely on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... At most, it should be counted against its commitments only the cost of the loan to the lending country (equivalent to an interest rate).
But France has nothing to do with such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1€ to meet its commitment, France only puts 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
That's a nice trick.
In short, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, it manages to make it believe that it is spending 420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy did the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it was enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter on early financing is only a small, relatively short-term issue in relation to all climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn the lessons of this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting method for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently under discussion): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
Hope therefore rests on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the discussions.
